Scenario: A team mutates shared state during render.
Code: 
let cache = [];
function ProductList({ products }) {
    cache.push(products.length);
    return products.map((p) => <ProductItem key={p.id} product={p} />);
}
Why is this implementation dangerous under concurrent rendering, and what architectural principle is being violated?

The architectural principle being violated is the principle of immutability and pure functions in React components. This is dangerous as the cache array is directly being mutauted
during the render phase, which can lead to unpredictable behavior and bugs, especially in concurrent rendering scenarios where multiple renders can happen simultaneously. 
In concurrent rendering, React may pause and resume renders, which can cause the cache to be updated in an inconsistent way, leading to race conditions and making it difficult to debug. 
This violates the principle of pure functions, which should not have side effects or mutate shared state during rendering.
